            <h3>Making Electoral Reform Fun!</h3>
        </div>
        <div id="blurb">
            <p>The Random Ballot is a voting system, and for you and me, it works much the same as voting currently does. You turn up at a polling station and mark your ‘X’ in the box next to the candidate that you’d like to represent your constituency in Parliament. But once all the ballots have been cast, instead of laboriously counting them to see who has the most votes, they are simply collected together and a single ballot paper is selected at random. Whichever candidate’s name is on the paper is that constituency’s new MP.</p>
            <p>Sounds crazy, right? Read on to find out why this system is not as madcap as it seems, or use the tool below to see how the 2017 election might have looked if it had been run using the Random Ballot system.</p>
